# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1885-st-louis-browns-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It played in the National Association league in 1875 and in the National League from 1876 to 1877.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] After a scandal over game-fixing, combined with financial problems, the St Louis Brown Stockings left the National League but continued to play as an independent team from 1878 to 1881.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Chris von der Ahe, a German immigrant, purchased the team prior to the 1882 season and joined the new American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings posted a 37-43 game record in their first season in the American Association, giving them fifth place.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played at the Grand Avenue Grounds (which was later renamed Sportsman's Park) at the corner of Grand Avenue and Dodier Street in north St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Before the 1882 season, Von der Ahe secured a place for the team in the American Association and provided funds to bring players to St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Between 1882 and 1892, the team he built went on to win four American Association titles.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Al Spink, the team advisor, recommended Von der Ahe sign Charlie Comiskey.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Comiskey, who later played with the Chicago White Sox, was a skilled, young, first baseman who had been playing in Dubuque, Iowa.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Ned Cuthbert was a former professional player in St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Although he had retired from baseball and worked as a bartender in St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, Cuthbert remained prominent in the local baseball community.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He had encouraged Von der Ahe to purchase the team.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Von der Ahe hired Cuthbert to be his first captain, with all the duties of a field manager.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Cuthbert used his experience to attract several players to St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Most of the first-year Browns originated in St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, including brothers Jack and Bill Gleason, pitcher Jumbo McGinnis, outfielder George Seward, and catcher Tom Sullivan.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In 1866, Gus Solari laid out a professional baseball field at Sportsman's Park, St Louis.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Sixteen years later, on May 2, 1882, the opening day of the St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings' 1882 season took place.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Approximately 2,000 spectators watched the game for a fee of one quarter each.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played numerous local teams in April exhibitions.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] McGinnis was the first pitcher and he started 45 of the team's 80 games.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It was a lead off single in the first innings.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He also scored the first run on Comiskey's three-base hit.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team won their first game with a score of 9 runs to 7.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In late May 1882, the team was in a tie for first place in its six-team league.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They were eight games over .500, putting them one game behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] There followed a seven-week period when the team lost sixteen more games than they won.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They could not contend for the championship.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] During the season, more than 175,000 spectators attended the team's games.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The favorite players on the team were Comiskey and McGinnis.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1883-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1883 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with a 66–32 record and won the championship of the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's second season in St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri and its second season in the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1883-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 65–33 during the season and finished second in the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1884 New York Metropolitans** finished with a 75–32 record, first place in the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] After the season, they played the National League champion Providence Grays in the 1884 World Series and lost three games to zero.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's third season in St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and its third season in the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1884-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 67–40 during the season and finished fourth in the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's fourth season in St.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and the fourth season in the American Association.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 79–33 during the season, best in the American Association, and won their first AA pennant.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] In the World Series, the Browns played the National League champion Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The series ended in dispute, with each club winning 3 games with 1 tie.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Manager Charlie Comiskey finally was able to assemble and direct a team from start to finish the way he wanted.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The team was built on daring baserunning, clutch hitting, and the best pitching in the league.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The team as a whole led the league in both earned run average (ERA) and overall runs allowed by a healthy margin over second-best Louisville.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] Individually, Dave Foutz was outstanding, as he won 33 of the 46 games he started and ranked fifth in ERA.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] His teammate Bob Caruthers was even better, compiling league-leading totals in wins (40), ERA (2.07) and winning percentage (a stellar .755).
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns took over first place to stay in the second week of May, but they made a joke of the race in July.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] On successive home stands, they had winning streaks of 17 and 12 games, combining for a major-league record 27-game winning streak at home that still stands as the best ever.
[src:1885-st-louis-browns-season/1885-st-louis-browns-season] They finished games laps ahead of the second-place Cincinnati Red Stockings and earned a berth in the World Series against the National League champion Chicago White Stockings.
